Jones played every snap against the Bills and should continue to do so in a system that has proven to be kind to LB1 types. Tap Jones as an LB2 for Week 9, but it shouldn't be long until we can once again comfortably count him as a top-12 option regardless of opponent.

Nakobe was excellent in Week 8, reeling off seven solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Nakobe has registered five or more solos in four straight games and in five of his seven contests overall. Dean has solidified himself as a strong LB2 with LB1 upside and should be treated as such for a plus Week 9 matchup against a banged-up Jacksonville Jaguars offense.

Pace was excellent in Week 8, tallying seven solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. Pace has been elite when healthy and should be considered a top-15 option until he cools down. Treat him as such for what is now more of a neutral Week 9 matchup against Joe Flacco and the Indianapolis Colts.

Baun was excellent in Week 8, tallying eight solos, four assists, and one forced fumble. Baun was quiet for a few weeks but seems to have things trending in the right direction after this spike week. Baun reeled off three strong weeks in a row to start the season, so hopefully, this is the start of another. Baun is an LB1 option for Week 9. Start him with confidence.

Okereke was excellent in Week 8, tallying seven solos, seven assists, 0.5 sacks, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. Okereke has been inconsistent in the solo department, but spike weeks have kept him in the LB2 conversation. Treat him as such for a plus Week 9 matchup against Washington.

Jewell returned in Week 8, racking up six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Jewell is an easy LB3 until he starts to heat up and should be rostered in all three LB leagues. Make the add where available.

Anzalone was at it again in Week 8, reeling off six solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The LB22 in fantasy points per game, Anzalone should continue to be trusted as a top-25 option for Week 9, thanks to a plus matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Elliss showed up in Week 8, tallying seven solos and four assists. Elliss slipped to LB3 territory after a string of slow weeks in the solo department, but outings like this serve to accentuate his LB2 upside. Tap him as an elite LB3 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Henley showed up in Week 8, racking up six solos, five assists, and one pass defended. Henley has been inconsistent in 202 but has shown flashes. He has been productive enough to be an LB3 option, as he has recorded four or more solos in six of his seven games played but has only recorded five or more on three occasions. Henley should be started where possible for Week 9 as an elite LB3 option, thanks to a plus matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Overshown showed up in Week 8, registering three solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Overshown has been an impact IDP producer since pushing Damone Clark to more of a reserve role as opposed to a rotational role, and is a borderline LB2 option. Treat him as an elite LB3 for a tough on-paper Week 9 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons. Make the add where available.

Cooper was excellent in Week 8, racking up five solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Cooper has flashed in recent weeks, but the emergence of Eric Wilson complicates matters once Quay Walker returns from concussion protocol. Wilson played every snap in Week 8, so Cooper is too risky of a play on a light bye. Take a wait-and-see approach here, as Cooper can provide serious dividends down the stretch, but keep Cooper glued to benches for Week 9.

Diabate was excellent in Week 8, tallying five solos, four assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended on 87 percent of the snaps. He should see an expanded role again this week, with Jeremiah Owusu-Koramoah (neck) already ruled out and Jordan Hicks (elbow/triceps) looking likely to join him after missing the first two practices of the week. Diabate makes for an intriguing LB3 option for Week 9, especially for those in deeper leagues, thanks to a plus matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers. Start him where needed.

Werner exploded in his return to action in Week 8, racking up seven solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss on 98 percent of the snaps. Willie Gay has played his way into a reserve role, so Werner should dominate snaps in two linebacker sets. Werner should solidify himself as an LB3 with LB2 upside over the next couple of games, starting with this week's plus matchup against the Carolina Panthers. Add Werner wherever available.

Ojulari showed up in Week 8, tallying three solos, four assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Ojulari is up to six sacks on the season, but five of his six sacks have come in his last three games alone. Azeez has bullied his way into the top-25 conversation and should be treated as a top-20 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against Washington. Start Ojulari everywhere while he is cooking.

Kyle Hamilton did Kyle Hamilton things in Week 8, racking up nine solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and two passes defended. Hamilton is locked in as a DB1 option, but outings like this highlight his DB1 upside.

Budda was excellent in Week 8, tallying six solos, six assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. The DB2 on the season, Baker is an elite play for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Bates showed up in Week 8, tallying three solos, two assists, one forced fumble, one fumble recovery, one interception, and one pass defended. Bates has been inconsistent in the solo department but has been buoyed by interceptions and forced fumbles. The DB10 on the season, Bates can continue to be started as a DB1 option.
Jones was excellent in Week 8, racking up seven solos and five assists. Jones has been inconsistent in the solo department but has registered seven or more solos in two of his last three games.

Moehrig was excellent in Week 8, tallying five solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Moehrig has yet to crack the DB2 conversation but has still been an excellent DB3. He has recorded five or more solos in three contests and has registered four or more in seven of his eight games played. Add and start Moehrig as a DB3 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Delpit was solid in Week 8, notching five solos and four assists. Delpit has been a bit of a disappointment in the IDP realm but has recorded five or more solos in four of his six complete contests. He remains more DB3 than DB2 but should be part of the top-25 conversation when he has plus matchups. Treat Delpit as a DB3 for a neutral at best Week 9 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers. Add Delpit where needed.

Thompson showed up in Week 8, tallying eight solos and three assists against the Miami Dolphins. The DB23 on the season after the strong outing, Thompson should be considered a top-25 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Chicago Bears. Start him with confidence as a DB2.

Joseph was excellent in Week 8, racking up five solos, one assist, one interception, and two passes defended. The DB16/S11 on the season, Kerby should continue to be fired up as a top-15 option for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Smith was excellent in Week 8, tallying six solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. Harrison has been more DB3 than DB2 this season but still has his spike weeks. He has recorded five or more solos just twice in seven games but has hit four or more in four of his last five. Treat him as an upside DB3 for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Pitre was solid in Week 8, tallying three solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. The DB25 on the season, Pitre is still more DB3 than DB2 but can be tapped as a DB2 play where required. Act accordingly for a plus Week 9 matchup against the New York Jets.

Izien showed up in Week 8, racking up seven solos, two assists, and two tackles of loss. Izien has had some down weeks but has been a force this season with five or more solos in four of his seven games played. Treat him as a DB3 with easy DB2 upside for a plus Week 9 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs on Monday Night Football.

Demani saw an expanded role in Week 8 due to injuries to Jammie Robinson, Nick Scott, and Jordan Fuller and responded with seven solos and four assists. He should get some more burn for the Panthers in what is already a lost season, especially with Scott and Fuller being veteran talents who are known values. Richardson is more of a deep league speculative add, as we still do not know the Week 9 status of the other injured defensive backs. Make the add where needed.
